Subject: Re: [neat] Self-adaptive Mutation Rates, Novelty Search and CMA-ES





Hello Joel and Vassilis,



I&#39;ll respond in this thread since it is focused on the issue of
self-adatptive mutation rates and novelty search. I&#39;ll first respond to
Vassilis then Joel&#39;s original comments. Please see below. 



Self-adaptive mutation rates are a terrible idea:

Jeff, thanks for pointing this out. That is an interesting paper! To be
honest I haven&#39;t read it before; so, you are saying that self-adaptive
mutation rates can be more effective on smoother fitness landscapes,
correct?



Novelty Search:

Joel, could novelty search be seen as a way of creating a smoother fitness
landscape? If yes, then based on what you said, is this the reason why
self-adaptive mutation rates work better when coupled with novelty search?





I agree with you. Self-adaptive mutation rates work fine on smooth
landscapes. Of course, landscapes on any interesting, non-trivial problem
are rugged, so that means that generally self-adaptive mutation rates are a
very bad idea. Novelty search, however, makes the conversation more complex.
I agree with you that NS smoothes out landscapes, making self-adaptive
mutation rates far less pathological. That said, I&#39;m not yet sure that
self-adaptive mutation rates are actually a good idea with Novelty Search
(see below). 







I believe the idea of self-adaptive mutation rates formed the basis for more
advanced evolution strategies such as CMA-ES. I am not trying to defend
CMA-ES here, which I agree with Jeff that it works differently than the
basic approach of encoding the mutation rates in the genotype. However, I am
wondering whether a combination of novelty search with CMA-ES would be a
good approach in speeding up the search for novel behaviours.



Of course, I can see some disadvantages of CMA-ES, an example being that the
genotype is a vector of real numbers with a fixed size... What do you think?





I don&#39;t think what makes CMA-ES effective has anything to do with
self-adaptive mutation rates. I think that it&#39;s advantage is in learning
correlations. But, as far as I know, it&#39;s still forced to mutate genomes
according to those correlations. I must admit I don&#39;t know the CMA_ES
literature at all, but my guess is that if you tried CMA-ES with and without
a mutation rate on the genome, you&#39;d get the same result I report in my
paper: as long as the landscape is rugged (i.e. the problem is non-trivial),
evolution will floor mutation rates and the result will underperform the
best, fixed mutation rate. Anyone know the literature enough to know if I&#39;m
right? Or anyone care to give it a try?



Regarding Joel&#39;s claim that whether self-adaptation is a good idea depends
on whether fitness is based on an objective or NS:



I love Joel and Ken&#39;s paper looking into whether self-adaptative mutation
rates (SAMR) are a better idea with NS. As I said above, it makes sense that
SAMR would be less bad with NS, because NS smooths out landscapes and
eliminates peaks, but is it actually a *good* idea instead of just being
less bad? On that question I am still agnostic pending further research. 



One reason is because of &quot;novelty plateaus&quot;, a concept my students and I
introduce in our last, not-yet-announced GECCO paper. Novelty plateaus exist
when, during novelty search, mutating the current population does not
immediately produce new behaviors. For example, once the low-hanging fruit
is consumed, it might take 5 specific mutations to produce a new behavior
(assume that all intermediate mutations have no effect on behavior). In that
case, NS cannot reward those stepping stones to the new behavior, and thus
there is no incentive to have a high mutation rate. Since most mutations
break things (producing the very un-novel behavior of doing little or
nothing), I hypothesize that having a high mutation rate will be selected
against when on such a novelty plateau. In other words, think of the long,
flat lines of fitness you (Joel) mentioned: We hypothesize that those
long-flat lines also exist in terms of generating new behaviors and, if
we&#39;re right, I think there would be a pressure to lower mutation rates
during such periods, even though keeping the mutation rate high is exactly
what you need to cross the plateau. Of course, a lot of this is speculation,
and I think a paper on this subject would be very interesting and worthwhile
for the community.



Now let me argue against myself, since I&#39;m thinking through these issues by
writing about them in this thread! While I can imagine that novelty plateaus
exist, for the specific purposes of this conversation on mutation rates, I
can&#39;t figure out if they would actually cause selection for lower mutation
rates, because even if you are not generating not-yet-seen-before behaviors,
you can be generating non-new behaviors in different regions of density in
the archive.meaning that you may truly always be on the side of a hill and
not on a neutral plateau. What do y&#39;all think?



An additional reason I&#39;m not yet ready to commit to the claim that SAMR is a
good idea with NS is because your paper didn&#39;t show that SAMR did optimize
mutation rates for long-term adaptation. You did not sweep over the range of
fixed mutation rates and show that SAMR found those optimal rates, or
outperformed them. Instead, you showed that it performed better than the
parameters you had for the initial experiment. 



An final reason I&#39;m agnostic (so far) on the issue of whether SAMR helps
with NS is because the evidence in your paper, while very interesting, was
also not overly strong or consistent. I hope you won&#39;t be offended and think
I&#39;m critical of you and Ken or the work. You may be right that SAMR+NS
works, and it would be fascinating if you are, but I would just like to see
larger effect sizes, lower p-values, and more consistency across domains
before taking the claim &quot;SAMR works with NS&quot; to the bank. Please see below
for some of my specific reasons for this claim. 



1. I don&#39;t see self-adaptive mutation rates helping a lot in your results:
in some cases SAMR improved evolvability significantly, but not in all, and
in the cases where the difference is significant, the effect size is very
small and the variance and associated p-value are high. The same is true for
performance, where self-adaptation only helped in one domain, not all, and
the difference was a jump from ~5% to ~10% (a doubling, which is rather
impressive, but with a p-value of only &lt; 0.05). I hope I didn&#39;t get any of
these details wrong. I apologize if I did.  



Personally I&#39;d prefer more tests before I really commit to this conclusion
and start drawing inferences from it. To repeat, I hope you don&#39;t mind that
I point out that I&#39;d prefer more experiments and on more problems before
fully committing to the view that self-adaptation helps with novelty search.
As I said, I do think the result is probably right, as self-adaptation works
well on smooth fitness landscapes, and NS does eliminate peaks and smooth
landscapes. Moreover, I think it was an extremely clever and interesting
question to ask and issue to raise: I&#39;m a big fan of the paper, but I&#39;d
still love to see follow-up studies on it because the result is fascinating,
but so far the evidence is not as strong as it could be. 



2. You show that Eibd* (&quot;evolvability as defined as producing immediate
behavioral diversity&quot;) is better for NS with self-adaptation, but

            a. The real proof is if these organisms actually evolve better
in a new environment. It would be great to see those data. You have provided
some evidence for improved long-term evolvability since performance was
higher, but again that was only in one of the domains, and the difference
was not huge. 

            b. Did you look at what happened to the mutation rates? They may
have still gone down, which could produce more Eibd, but at the cost of Elt*
(Evolvability over the Long Term). 



3. You report that &quot;Initial experiments revealed that evolving a single
mutation power and rate for each entire genome is too coarse.&quot; That suggests
that the effect may not be that robust, and may be hard to take advantage of
in practice. I also noted that in the treatment that ultimately worked, you
took an intermediate route of different mutation rates for different
connections, but not one set of mutation rates per-connection. Out of
curiosity, did you also try that and find it didn&#39;t work? 



Overall, I do think that how bad self-adaptive mutation rates are depends on
the ruggedness of landscapes, and NS makes them less bad because it smooths
landscapes. However, I consider the question of whether SAMR are beneficial
with NS to be a fascinating, open question that you have provided some
evidence for, but that we&#39;d all benefit from seeing a lot more research
into. 



Best,

Jeff



